To find the value of |(A x B) △ (B x A)|, we first need to find the Cartesian products A x B and B x A.

A x B = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3), (3, 2), (3, 3)}
B x A = {(2, 1), (2, 2), (2, 3), (3, 1), (3, 2), (3, 3)}

Now, we find the symmetric difference (△) between these two sets. The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements that are in either of the sets but not in their intersection.

Intersection of A x B and B x A:
(A x B) ∩ (B x A) = {(2, 2), (2, 3), (3, 2), (3, 3)}

Symmetric difference (△):
(A x B) △ (B x A) = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 1), (3, 1)}

Finally, we find the cardinality (| |) of the symmetric difference set:

|(A x B) △ (B x A)| = 4
